With her eyes tightly shut and her face covered with paint, sequins and paper flowers, Bulgarian bride Fatme Inus followed centuries of tradition in her village when she married her groom yesterday.

The practice of painting the bride's 
face white and decorating it with sequins and coloured paint is called 
'gelena' in Bulgarian and is unique to Fatme's home, the remote town of Ribnovo.

Ribnovo, set on a snowy mountainside in southwest Bulgaria, has kept its traditional winter marriage ceremony alive despite decades of Communist persecution, followed by poverty that forced many men to seek work abroad.

